function earliestAndLatest(n, firstPlayer, secondPlayer) {
    let earliest = 1, latest = 1;
    while ((firstPlayer + secondPlayer) !== n + 1 || Math.abs(firstPlayer - secondPlayer) !== 1) {
        if ((firstPlayer + secondPlayer) <= n + 1 && Math.floor((firstPlayer - 1) / 2) === Math.floor((secondPlayer - 1) / 2)) break;
        if ((firstPlayer + secondPlayer) > n + 1) {
            n = Math.floor((n + 1) / 2);
            [firstPlayer, secondPlayer] = [(n + 1) - secondPlayer, (n + 1) - firstPlayer];
        } else {
            firstPlayer = Math.floor((firstPlayer + 1) / 2);
            secondPlayer = Math.floor((secondPlayer + 1) / 2);
        }
        earliest++;
        latest++;
    }
    return [earliest, latest];
}
```

    The algorithm starts by initializing the `earliest` and `latest` round values as 1. It then iterates in a while loop until the sum of the player positions is `n + 1` and the absolute difference between their positions is 1 (since they can only compete when they are next to each other). In each iteration, it checks if they are in the same half of the row. If so, break the loop, as they cannot compete earlier. Then, if they are in opposite halves, reflect their position with respect to the middle of the row. Otherwise, update their position by going to the next round. Finally, increment the round numbers `earliest` and `latest`.

The while loop is the core of the algorithm, determining when the two players can meet. The logic within the loop keeps track of the players' positions in subsequent rounds, ensuring that the earliest and latest rounds are updated accordingly.

